article.headline: Hudson throws a 34-point birthday bash

images.name: McGrady_Tracy 020313 inline
images.caption: Tracy McGrady had 35 points, eight rebounds, eight assists, three steals and two blocked shots.

article.linkText: Hudson's B-Day play boosts Magic past Suns in OT
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Troy Hudson scored a career-high 34 points on his 26th birthday. His present arrived a few weeks ago from Orlando coach Doc Rivers.
Hudson

"I called him in my office and I told him he's a free man," Rivers said. '"You can go on the floor and basically create and do what you want with the ball. Just be aggressive every single time and I'll take you out every time I think you're not confident.' "He's not a point guard and we'll just live with that." Hudson sparked Orlando to its third consecutive home victory, 119-114 over Phoenix in overtime Wednesday night. He shot 14-of-23, including 5-of-10 on 3-pointers. "I came out with a lot of energy," Hudson said. "I've been with a lot of energy all day today, excited about my birthday. I performed well on the court tonight." So did teammate Tracy McGrady, who missed a game-winner in regulation but was dominant in overtime, scoring all 10 of Orlando's points on 4-of-6 shooting. McGrady finished with 35 points, shooting 14-of-28 and adding eight rebounds, eight assists, three steals and two blocked shots. "He just made the plays he's supposed to make," said Suns coach Frank Johnson, whose team has dropped three consecutive road games. Hudson and McGrady got plenty of help from Horace Grant, who had 17 points and nine rebounds, and Monty Williams, who scored 16. The Suns were led by Stephon Marbury with 31 points and 10 assists. Shawn Marion had 22 points and 13 rebounds. Joe Johnson scored 15 and Jake Tsakalidis had 11. "We had a little slump at the end of the first half but mostly we were playing good ball all night tonight," Marion said. "They hit some incredible shots from outside. It seemed they were knocking down almost every 3 tonight." McGrady began overtime by hitting his first two shots while Phoenix didn't make a field goal until 1:50 remained, closing Orlando's lead to 113-112 on Marion's basket. McGrady reeled off six consecutive points to put Orlando up 119-112 with 17.6 seconds remaining. The Suns shot 2-of-11 in overtime. "This is a tough building coming to, being back-to-back," said Phoenix's Penny Hardaway, who played six seasons in Orlando. "We knew they were going to play hard and we just wanted to match their intensity and we did until overtime. They made shots and we didn't." Marion hit a short jumper with 4.3 seconds remaining in regulation that tied the game at 109. After an Orlando timeout, McGrady had an isolation on Marion and drove to the basket, looking for a foul. McGrady didn't get the bucket or the call. "We kind of let our guard down throughout the game and they came back," McGrady said. "We gave them some life, forced it to overtime, so we had to take over in overtime and really put it on them." Orlando led by as many as 13 points in the third quarter thanks to a pair of 3-pointers Hudson hit at the end of the second period that put the Magic up 62-53 at the half. Dan Majerle's 3-pointer at 5:48 in the fourth gave Phoenix its first lead since early in the first quarter, 101-99. The game was tied four times in the final 4:31.

Game notes
Phoenix forward Tom Gugliotta did not play after injuring his foot during Tuesday's game at Miami. Gugliotta has missed 25 games this year. ... Orlando's Dee Brown played three minutes for his first action since last year's playoff series against Milwaukee. Brown retired Aug. 29 to work in Orlando's front office but was signed to a 10-day contract following Mike Miller's ankle injury. ... The Suns' Bo Outlaw played his first game in Orlando since being traded from the Magic on Nov. 16. He had four points and 11 rebounds. ... Orlando owner Rich DeVos addressed the crowd during halftime with a message of commitment to the Magic's current facility. DeVos had placed the team up for sale but changed his mind March 5. He was joined at halfcourt by Armstrong.
